These are the notes from the Canada West Foundation publication https://cwf.ca/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Agriculture-Sector-RTS-Report_Final.pdf

Four key areas:
- On-Farm Investment
- Market and product diversification
- Infrastructure
- Technology and INnovation

## On Farm Investment

- Federal funding is not intended for individual farm businesses
- Generational shift from family farm to the farm as a business. This is leading to new types of partnerships and investment models than was being considered before. Suggestion is to learn from the oil and gas industry.
- There may be a lack of investment in storage to manage the time between harvest and demand
- Crazy statistic that Alberta accounts for 80% of the total irrigation volume in Canada!
	- There is an Alberta irrigation project that started in 2020 with a proposed investment of over $800M to upgrade the irrigation infrastructure that would lead to over 200,000 more irrigated acres of farmland.  This is projected to contribute $60M/year 

## Market and Product Diversification

- Canadian farmers end up sending a lot of raw material overseas vs. more refined products.  Canola is seen as an example of a product that has large global demand. Lentils seen as an up and comer.
- Notes that the existing provincial barriers combined with the federal regulation for food processing makes trade in Canada more costly than sending overseas.
- The US and China dominate exports which has a higher risk due to the current tarriff stance for both countries.
- Proposal to have better market intelligence data to support identifying emerging opportunities and support the investment planning value stream

## Infrastructure

- The ability to make large capital investments is creating a supply chain bottleneck.  
- One example is the Second Narrows Bridge that is a single rail line that is aging that supplies the Port of Vancouver.
- Port of Prince Rupert is an example of successful investment to expand the export capacity for Canada

## Technology and Innovation

- There does not seem to be the environment to foster entrepreneurs developing new technology for the agriculture sector
- There is an example from Germany where an applied research institute was formed to look at the entire agriculture value chain to see where there might be opportunities for innovation.

## Toward a National Strategy

There apparently should be a strategy.
